1. Create your Google Sheet:
   a. Open Google Sheets and create a new spreadsheet.
   b. Rename it to something like "Calendar Events."
   c. Set up the columns you want, e.g., Event Name, Start Date, End Date, etc.

2. Write a Google Apps Script:
   a. Open Google Drive and click "New" then "More" and finally "Google Apps Script."
   b. Rename the new script project, e.g., "CalendarToSheet."
   c. Replace the default code with the following code:

```
function syncCalendarToSheet() {
  var calendar = CalendarApp.getDefaultCalendar();
  var sheet = SpreadsheetApp.openById('<your_spreadsheet_id>').getActiveSheet();
  var events = calendar.getEvents(new Date(), new Date(new Date().setDate(new Date().getDate() + 30)));

  sheet.clearContents();
  sheet.appendRow(['Event Name', 'Start Date', 'End Date']);

  for (var i = 0; i < events.length; i++) {
    sheet.appendRow([events[i].getTitle(), events[i].getStartTime(), events[i].getEndTime()]);
  }
}

function createTrigger() {
  ScriptApp.newTrigger('syncCalendarToSheet')
    .forSpreadsheet(SpreadsheetApp.getActiveSpreadsheet())
    .onEventUpdated()
    .create();
}
```

Make sure to replace `<your_spreadsheet_id>` with the actual ID of your Google Sheet (you can find it in your sheet's URL: `https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/<your_spreadsheet_id>/edit`).

3. Save the script by pressing Ctrl + S (Cmd + S on Mac), then close the script editor.

4. Deploy the script as a Google Sheets add-on:
   a. In the script editor, click "Publish" and select "Deploy as Sheets add-on."
   b. Fill in the required fields for the add-on, such as version, description, etc.
   c. Click "Deploy."

5. To enable the add-on, go to your Google Sheet and click "Extensions" in the menu bar, then select "Manage Extensions." Find your add-on and make sure it is enabled.

6. You may need to authorize the required permissions for the script via a prompt.

Now, whenever you create, update, or delete an event in your Google Calendar, the Google Sheet should be updated automatically with the current event data. If you don't see the changes, you may need to manually run the `syncCalendarToSheet` function by going back to your script editor, selecting the function, and clicking "Run."

